<paper id="1538319178"><title>Towards Making Luby-Rackoff Ciphers Optimal and Practical</title><year>1999</year><authors><author org="Lucent Technologies'" id="2125066154">Sarvar Patel</author><author org="massachusetts institute of technology" id="2778964226">Zulfikar Ramzan</author><author org="Lucent Technologies'" id="2489548834">Ganapathy S. Sundaram</author></authors><n_citation>29</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>206097255</reference><reference>1484296207</reference><reference>1490586645</reference><reference>1504217304</reference><reference>1552402248</reference><reference>1559931973</reference><reference>1566172292</reference><reference>1656678770</reference><reference>1887453827</reference><reference>1972464518</reference><reference>1985263989</reference><reference>2047505738</reference><reference>2077300005</reference><reference>2117362057</reference><reference>2131300413</reference><reference>2568739026</reference></references><venue id="2758283624" type="C">Fast Software Encryption</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-48519-8_13</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.67933">Block size</keyword><keyword weight="0.64499">S-box</keyword><keyword weight="0.605">T-function</keyword><keyword weight="0.66167">Key schedule</keyword><keyword weight="0.44407">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.62757">CBC-MAC</keyword><keyword weight="0.44634">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.59634">Galois/Counter Mode</keyword><keyword weight="0.62312">Linear cryptanalysis</keyword><keyword weight="0.63701">Differential cryptanalysis</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>We provide new constructions for Luby-Rackoff block ciphers which are efficient in terms of computations and key material used. Next, we show that we can make some security guarantees for Luby-Rackoff block ciphers under much weaker and more practical assumptions about the underlying function; namely, that the underlying function is a secure Message Authentication Code. Finally, we provide a SHA-1 based example block cipher called Sha-zam.</abstract></paper>